(105, 2, '2012-02-24 12:32:45', '2012-02-24 19:32:45', 'Get a free email critique of your current resume.  Send it to info@compassrosecareers.com and I will respond by email with my evaluation of the document''s strengths and areas to be improved.', 'Free Critique of Your Current Resume', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'free-critique-of-your-current-resume', '', '', '2012-02-24 12:32:45', '2012-02-24 19:32:45', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=105', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(141, 2, '2012-03-27 21:16:41', '2012-03-28 03:16:41', 'Check out the examples of the two basic kinds of resumes on the\n<a title="Resumes" href="http://compassrosecareers.com/resumes/">Resumes</a> page', 'Sample Resumes', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'sample-resumes', '', '', '2012-03-27 21:16:41', '2012-03-28 03:16:41', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=141', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(161, 2, '2012-06-11 15:51:38', '2012-06-11 21:51:38', '<strong><em>Do you need a test to tell you what you like? </em></strong>\n\nCareer interest tests predict what jobs, career areas and types of organizations will fit you best.  They do this by analyzing your responses<em> </em>to questions describing activities, school subjects, careers, and types of people. Interest tests help you understand how your likes and dislikes translate into career choices.\n\n<strong><em>They work because most of us do best at things we enjoy . . .  obvious but also true! </em></strong>\n\nBut what if you’re not sure what you like?  Maybe you like a lot of things.  Maybe you haven’t worked in a lot of different jobs, so you don’t have a way to compare.\n\nThe occupations and career areas suggested by an interest test are meant to suggest ideas for your own research, not tell you what to do.  Use the results as one piece of the puzzle that you’re putting together.  You may get ideas from your test results that you’ve never thought about.\n\n<strong>Remember,  most people who are successful like what they.</strong> They go with their strengths.  Your strengths and your interests are two sides of the same coin.\n\n&nbsp;', 'Career Interest Tests', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'career-interest-tests', '', '', '2012-06-11 15:51:38', '2012-06-11 21:51:38', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=161', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(165, 2, '2012-06-11 16:10:19', '2012-06-11 22:10:19', '<strong></strong>When choosing a career interest test, pick one that has a solid history.  The <strong>Strong Interest Inventor</strong>y is the most widely used instrument.  Your scores are compared to all the scores of thousands of different employees in hundreds of occupations who have taken the same test.  The scoring is so complex a computer must do it, but the test is easy to take in about 20-30 minutes. The Strong is used by career counselors, coaches, and college counseling centers.  You might be able to take it free at your local college.  If you take a paper and pencil version, it must be sent to a testing center and scored by a computer, so expect your results in about a week.  The Strong uses the Holland system of classifying interests.  This gives you a 3-letter score of how you scored on Realistic, Investigative, Artistic, Social, Enterprising, and Conventional occupations.\n\nThe <strong>Self Directed Search</strong> is also based on the Holland system.  You get a report with your 3-letter Holland Code and a list of occupations to research.  It takes about 20 minutes online and the fee is $4.95.  <a title="Self Directed Search" href="http://www.self-directed-search.com" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">www.self-directed-search.com</span></a>\n\nThe <strong>Career Key</strong> was developed by Dr. Lawrence Jones as a public service and has been validated on large number of people. The test costs $9.95 to take. If you know your Holland Code, you can use the site to research careers and occupational descriptions.  <a title="Career Key" href="http://www.careerkey.org" target="_blank"><span style="text-decoration: underline;">www.careerkey.org</span></a>\n\nThe <strong>O’Net Interest Profiler</strong> is the Department of Labor’s instrument. It is free and the site contains useful information on job descriptions and skills.  You can look up any job title and find extensive descriptions of the job duties and required skills. You can even check out the average salaries for any job, nationally and by state. To take the ONet Interest Profiler go to <a title="ONET Interest Profiler" href="http://www.careerinfonet.org/explore/view.aspx" target="_blank">www.careerinfonet.org/explore/view.aspx</a>. Look for Interest Profiler.  You have to download the software, but it’s quick and easy.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Where Can I Take an Interest Test?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'where-can-i-take-an-interest-test', '', '', '2012-06-11 16:10:19', '2012-06-11 22:10:19', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=165', 0, 'post', '', 3),
(182, 2, '2012-06-13 18:04:43', '2012-06-14 00:04:43', 'Holland’s theory is that there are six kinds of people and six kinds of work environments. If you know you’re 3-letter Holland code, you can relate your characteristics to many kinds of jobs.\n\n<strong><em>Realistic</em></strong> people like to work with machines, tools, and numbers. They prefer less involvement with people. They have mechanical aptitude and like physical challenges. They like to work outdoors and on activities where they accomplish tasks by DOING, like building and repairing.\n<p align="left"><strong><em>I or Investigative</em></strong> people like to work with data, numbers, tools, and machines more than people. They like work environments that involve observing, learning, evaluating, and thinking through problems. They do not enjoy structured settings and are often creative in scientific areas. They like to achieve by THINKING.</p>\n<p align="left"><strong><em>A for Artistic </em></strong>people like work environments that are unstructured and allow for personal expression and creative work. They prefer working with words, images, and numbers, less with people. They like to work alone. The achieve by CREATING.</p>\n<p align="left"><strong><em>S for Social</em></strong> people who like to help others. They like to work with people, in groups and in organizations where they can be concerned about the well being of others. They like to use their communication skills at work. They are less interested in data, tools, and machines. They achieve by HELPING.</p>\n<p align="left"><strong><em>E is for enterprising</em></strong> people who like environments where they can lead, persuade, and manage people, where competition is important and taking risks leads to success. They enjoy work environments with high involvement with people and low involvement with machines. They enjoy persuading others and are impatient with precise work. They achieve by PERSUADING.</p>\n<p align="left"><strong><em> C is for Conventional</em></strong> people who like work environments where they can follow routines, meet standards, and be responsible, using clerical and math abilities and organizing. They like low involvement with people; low-moderate with tools and machines and moderate involvement with words and numbers. They do not seek leadership and they value contributing to an organization within an established chain of command. They achieve by FOLLOWING RULES.</p>\n<p align="left"></p>', 'What Kinds of Work Do You Like? The Holland Codes', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-kinds-of-work-do-you-like-the-holland-codes', '', '', '2012-06-13 18:04:43', '2012-06-14 00:04:43', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=182', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(187, 2, '2012-06-13 18:18:48', '2012-06-14 00:18:48', 'Personality tests help you understand yourself so you can make better career decisions.\n\nThey will:\n<ul>\n	<li>understand yourself and others</li>\n	<li>identify what careers people who are like you prefer and are successful doing</li>\n	<li>understand how personality traits suggest potential careers</li>\n</ul>\nThe best personality tests have been around for a long time.  They have been validated on many people and found to predict success in both school and work situations.\n\nThe Meyers Briggs Type Indicator gives you a four-letter “type” score based on four preferences:  Extraversion/Introversion; Sensing/Intuition; Thinking/Feeling; Judging/Perceiving.  Type has been correlated with college majors, jobs, career areas, goal-setting, making decisions, job satisfaction and interpersonal relationships.\n\nI have used this instrument extensively and have found it as helpful as the Strong in working with people in transition. Your type can be taken online in about 30 minutes.  Here are two sites that offer it free of charge\n\n<a title="Human Metrics" href="http://humanmetrics.com">http://www. humanmetrics.com/</a>\n\n<a title="Keirsey Temperaments" href="http://www.keirsey.com"> http://www.keirsey.com</a>', 'What''s Your Type?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'whats-your-type', '', '', '2012-06-13 18:18:48', '2012-06-14 00:18:48', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=187', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(199, 2, '2012-06-28 15:40:45', '2012-06-28 21:40:45', '<p style="text-align: left;" align="center"><strong> </strong>When you send a resume to an employer, by email, fax, or snail mail, always send a covering letter with it. The letter introduces you to the recipient, says what you are looking for, and requests an appointment. It should be written in professional but friendly languagand encourage the reader to look at your resume.</p>\n Cover letters should be brief, specifically targeted to the organization, and addressed to an individual. If you don’t know the name of the person you need to write to, find out. No one is impressed with a form letter.\n\nWhile a resume is written for a particular type of position and may apply to jobs in many different organizations, the letter is directed to a specific job.\n\nCover these points in each letter:\n\n1. State who you are and why you are writing. If you’ve been referred by someone else, mention the name, company, and title in the first paragraph. Mention the position for which you are applying.\n\n2.  State briefly, in one or two paragraphs, why you are qualified for the position.     Mention two or three accomplishments that relate to the position you are  targeting. Do not repeat what is in your resume.\n\n3. Make a positive statement about the company/department. If you know nothing about the company, go online and find out what has been written about it recently in the business press. Check out the company’s website.\n\n4. Request an interview. Be assertive. State when you will place a follow-up call about an appointment. Thank the recipient for reading your resume and letter.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Cover Letters Are a Must', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'cover-letters-are-a-must', '', '', '2012-06-28 15:40:45', '2012-06-28 21:40:45', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=199', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(205, 2, '2012-06-28 15:55:31', '2012-06-28 21:55:31', 'Here is a quick method to get you thinking about what you really want to do.  Try using these four simple steps to clarify your goal.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n1.   Choose one or two of your favorite skills/talents/abilities and complete the following sentence:\n\nMy goal is to use my ________________________\n\n<strong>Example:  My goal is to use my communication skills . . .</strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n2.   Review your list of action words to find the action you can see yourself doing in relation to your general skill area.\n<p style="text-align: justify;">   <em>       Some action words include:</em>   assist, promote, guide, promote, motivate, discover, organize, sell,</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">            stimulate, encourage, persuade, help, interpret, activate, manage, teach, organiz</p>\n<p style="text-align: justify;">My goal is to use my _____________skills to____________ people to . .</p>\n<strong>Example: <em>My goal is to use my communication skills to support people to . . . </em></strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n3. Decide if you want to qualify what type of people you want to be working with. For example, women, minorities, rich, poor, etc.\n\nMy goal is to use my ____________skills to ____________women to . . .\n\n<strong>Example:  <em>My goal is to use my communication skills to help women to . . . </em></strong>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n4.  What  is the final product you''d like to see in that other person?  What is the result of your work with him/her. In the example, I need to determine what it is I want to help women to BE, DO or HAVE\n\n<strong>THE COMPLETED EXAMPLE:  <em>My goal is to use my communication skills to help women find better jobs.  </em></strong>\n<p style="text-align: center;"><em><strong>What is your goal?</strong></em></p>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'A Quick Way to Clarify Your Career Goal', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'a-quick-way-to-clarify-your-career-goal', '', '', '2012-06-28 15:55:31', '2012-06-28 21:55:31', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=205', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(215, 2, '2012-07-05 13:30:59', '2012-07-05 19:30:59', 'If you are in transition because you were laid off, your company downsized, you don''t like what you''ve\ndone in the past, or you see future opportunities shrinking in your field, it pays to take some time and think about what you want in your next position.   These are some questions to get you started.\n\n<em>To make my transition, I might need to change….</em>\n\n<em> </em>\n\n<em>If things to well in the next five years, I will be doing:</em>\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em> If things do not go well in the next five years, I will be doing:</em>\n\n<em> </em>\n\n<em>Who Am I? </em>\n\n<em>________________________________________</em>\n\n<em>________________________________________</em>\n\n_______________________________________\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<em> </em><em> What are my strongest skills?</em>\n\n<em> </em>\n\n<em>What do I want most in my next position? </em>\n\n<em> </em>\n\n<em> </em><em>What kinds of problems do I want to solve? </em>\n\n<em> </em>\n\n<em> </em><em>Who is in my network? </em>\n\n<em> </em>\n\n<em> </em><em>What is my next step? </em>\n\n&nbsp;', 'Some Questions To Ask Yourself if You''re in Transition', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'some-questions-to-ask-yourself-if-youre-in-transition', '', '', '2012-07-05 13:30:59', '2012-07-05 19:30:59', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=215', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(235, 2, '2012-07-15 13:45:32', '2012-07-15 19:45:32', '<p style="text-align: left;" align="center"><strong></strong>Many people ask me what are good questions to ask in a job interview.  Here are a few examples:</p>\n\n<ul>\n	<li>What do you see as this position''s responsibilities on a regular basis?</li>\n	<li>What are the <em>most</em> important responsibilities of this position?</li>\n	<li>What was the reason for this position''s vacancy? (</li>\n	<li>How long does the average employee remain with your company?</li>\n	<li>What are this company’s current challenges?</li>\n	<li>What do you view as this company’s greatest goals and missions?</li>\n	<li>Has this company experienced a downsizing at any time in its history, and if so, when?</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;', 'Questions You Can Ask an Employer In a Job Interview', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'questions-you-can-ask-an-employer-in-a-job-interview', '', '', '2012-07-15 13:45:32', '2012-07-15 19:45:32', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=235', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(250, 2, '2012-08-07 15:16:22', '2012-08-07 21:16:22', 'You can do a few simple things to assure your resume does not end up in the\n“No” pile.\n<ol>\n	<li> If you use an objective, list the job for which you are applying.  No long flowery statements about what you want or hope to achieve. A tight focus is best. If you’re tight for space, the objective can be eliminated on the resume and put into the cover letter.</li>\n	<li>Neat, clean, and easy to read. No fancy fonts. No graphics or pictures (unless you’re a graphic artist). Use one font and change the size for headers. Leave plenty of white space or it will be unreadable. The most important information should be in the top one third of the first page.</li>\n	<li> Focus on accomplishments, not job duties. What made you different (and better!) than everyone else who did the same job? What did you contribute? What were the results of your work?</li>\n	<li>Omit extraneous information not related to the job in question. No hobbies, memberships, interests, or jobs that do not support your job goal.</li>\n	<li> Use a chronological format or a combination functional/chronological format. A straight functional resume is often not accepted by employers.</li>\n</ol>', 'Five Ways To Make Your Resume Stand Out From the Crowd!', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'five-ways-to-make-your-resume-stand-out-from-the-crowd', '', '', '2012-08-07 15:16:22', '2012-08-07 21:16:22', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=250', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(257, 2, '2012-08-08 13:31:56', '2012-08-08 19:31:56', 'Some people think the more information they include on a resume, the better. This is NOT true. Only include what will support your job goal and convince the person reading it to contact you for an interview.\n\nSome things you DO NOT include are:\n<ul>\n	<li>Salary information - can be used to screen you out</li>\n	<li>Photograph – can be used to discriminate against you</li>\n	<li>Date of birth, marital status, children – all items that can be used to discriminate. It is illegal for an employer to ask you about these items, so why volunteer them?</li>\n	<li>Reasons for leaving a job – this is for a formal application, not a resume</li>\n	<li>Start date – listing this can make you look desperate. Don’t bring it up unless you are asked in an interview</li>\n	<li>References – are not included on the resume, but on a separate sheet that you   provide the employer only when asked to do so</li>\n</ul>\nUse the resume to highlight your measurable achievements, work history, and relevant education to make the best impression.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'What NOT to Include On Your Resume', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-not-to-include-on-your-resume', '', '', '2012-08-08 13:31:56', '2012-08-08 19:31:56', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=257', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(260, 2, '2012-08-15 12:53:26', '2012-08-15 18:53:26', 'Clear, concise language gives the impression that you are a serious, professional  job applicant. There are some simple things you can do to make sure your document presents you in the best possible light.\n<ul>\n	<li> Start every sentence in your Summary and Professional Experience sections with an action verb. Always use the past tense. For example: Taught; supervised; delivered; organized; trained; managed. Avoid passive constructions like “a report was developed.” Say “researched and wrote a report.”</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Be concise. Shorter is better. Don’t use flowery phrases, clichés, or excessive adjectives. Everyone is busy and by being brief, you are showing that you respect the employer’s time.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li> Don’t use jargon or buzzwords. Say what you did, how well you did it, and what the results were of your effort in simple, clear words.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Be specific. Avoid general phrases that sound like a generic job description. Don’t say “taught classes”; instead say, “taught MS Word basic skills to ten newly hired administrative employees per month.”</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Don’t depend on spell check. Have someone read your document for typos, misspellings, and grammatical errors.</li>\n</ul>\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'Does Your Resume Pass the Language Test?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'does-your-resume-pass-the-language-tes', '', '', '2012-08-15 12:53:26', '2012-08-15 18:53:26', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=260', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(266, 2, '2012-08-16 13:22:41', '2012-08-16 19:22:41', 'How you organize your resume matters. Employers look for skills, accomplishments, experience, and education that directly relates to their needs. The most important information about you, what will sell you most strongly, should be in the top half of the first page of your resume.\n\nUse a Chronological Format if your most recent work experience relates directly to your job goal. List your jobs in date order starting with the most recent. If your career has progressed in an orderly way, this is the most effective way to present your skills.\n\nUse a Functional Format if your skills and experience are in several different fields, if you have breaks of time in your work record, or if you are returning to the job market. Use a Summary to present your strongest skills as the first item, and list your jobs at the bottom. Note:  some employers do not like the   Functional Format because they want to know where you acquired your skills.\n\nUse the Combination Format (first page a summary of functional skills; second  page a chronological listing of work experience) if you have more than 15 years of diverse experience, if you have worked in many different industries or if you are changing careers. When done well, this format can be very effective.\n\nNo matter what format you choose, your resume must look clear and attractive, with plenty of “white space” and no unusual fonts or graphics.\n\n&nbsp;', 'What Format Is Best for You?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-format-is-best-for-you', '', '', '2012-08-16 13:22:41', '2012-08-16 19:22:41', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=266', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(270, 2, '2012-08-24 12:57:21', '2012-08-24 18:57:21', 'To make sure your resume goes to the top of the pile, be sure you have included a clear description of your accomplishments on each recent job.\n\nAccomplishments are NOT job descriptions. They are NOT a list of job duties. They are NOT generic. So what are they?\n\nAccomplishments are specific statements of what you did, how well you did it, and the results of your efforts.\n\nThink about what you did differently than every other person in your organization that had a similar job.\n\n<strong> <em>Examples of results-driven accomplishment statements</em></strong>\n\n<em></em>Researched and wrote a 40-page training manual that was used to train 10 new sales representatives per month on company policies and sales techniques.\n\nDeveloped a new filing system that significantly reduced filing time for administrative staff, resulting in higher productivity and higher customer satisfaction as measured by annual surveys.\n\nAs an exercise, look at your current resume. Choose one statement about what you did from your most recent job. Is it specific? Does it include results? Are the results measured in some way? Could the employer reading it tell if you will bring value to her company?\n\nIt is worth the time to rewrite your job duties as accomplishment statements. Be sure to start each sentence with an action verb in the past tense!', 'What Makes a Great Resume?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-makes-a-great-resume', '', '', '2012-08-24 12:57:21', '2012-08-24 18:57:21', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=270', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(274, 2, '2012-08-25 09:11:15', '2012-08-25 15:11:15', 'You can’t write a great resume without knowing what you’re going to do with it. A generic document will not take you far in this job market. But how do you know what a company looks for?  Good question. And the only way you can answer it is to research the company.\n\n<strong> The Internet </strong>\n\nThe good news is that you can learn a lot just by searching the web. Check out the company’s website. Look for their mission statement, what their public relations department has put out about them. Check out their job descriptions.\n\n<strong> Industry Publications</strong>\n\nAnother resource is industry publications. If you keep up to date on what’s going on, you’ll have a better chance of a meaningful connection during an interview.\n\n<strong> Business Press</strong>\n\nFor large companies, check both the local and national presses. Search for articles about what the company is doing, what new personnel have been hired, community involvement, new acquisitions.\n\n<strong>Networking </strong>\n\nUse your networking contacts to find someone who works in the company. Insider information is often the best source for how to present yourself.\n\n<strong>Culture</strong>\n\nIf you learn about the values and culture of a company, it’s much easier to tailor the language on your resume to match. Is it a highly formal organization? A more casual or collaborative environment? Do they value teamwork? Achievement? Academic qualifications?\n\nThe more you learn about your target organizations, and incorporate what you learn into your resume, the more likely your resume will go into the “YES” pile.', 'How to Tailor Your Resume to a Company', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'how-to-tailor-your-resume-to-a-company', '', '', '2012-08-25 09:11:15', '2012-08-25 15:11:15', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=274', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(282, 2, '2012-11-09 13:07:28', '2012-11-09 20:07:28', 'If you’re called for an interview, chances are you’re qualified for the job. You have the education, experience, and skills they want, based on your resume.\n\nBut during the interview, how do employers discriminate among several qualified candidates?\n\nResearch shows that employers are usually looking for certain personality traits such as confidence, positive communication, high energy, and professionalism.\n\nWhen you walk into an interview, be prepared. Do your homework. Learn as much as you can about the company, its current challenges, and its culture.\n\nDo enough research that you can be dressed appropriately for their culture. Employers are looking for people who will fit in without effort.\n\nBe upbeat. Start the interview with a firm handshake. Smile. Tell the interviewer that you’re glad to be there and why. If you don’t, others will.\n\nDuring the interview, mention how you have achieved results in previous positions. Mention accomplishments that show you are a self-starter with initiative. If you saved money or time, developed new projects, or came up solutions to problems, you will make a positive impression!\n\nAnd don’t forget to use the <strong>SAR</strong> formula when talking about what you’ve done.\n\nMention the <strong>situation</strong>\n\nWhat <strong>action</strong> you took\n\nWhat <strong>results</strong> you achieved.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'What Do Employers Want?', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'what-do-employers-want', '', '', '2012-11-09 13:07:28', '2012-11-09 20:07:28', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=282', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(309, 2, '2012-11-12 12:05:27', '2012-11-12 19:05:27', 'After every contact with an employer--job interview, informational interview, phone call--follow up with a personal letter, email or call.\n\nWhich method works best depends upon the employer and the level of interaction.\n\nIf you went through a formal job interview, a letter is the most conservative way to follow up.  It doesn''t have to be long.  Just a brief statement of how much you enjoyed meeting the employer and that you are interested in the job is sufficient.  However, if you forgot to mention something important in the interview, this is a great opportunity to bring it up.  Or maybe you''ve had an idea on how the employer might solve a problem or challenge that came up during the interview.  This is your chance to shine!\n\nIf your interactions with the employer have been via email, then an email message might be fine. Another reason to be sure to get the employer''s business card during the interview.\n\nA followup should be done within a few days of the interview. Remember, it will make you stand out, so a little extra effort is worth the time you put in.\n\n&nbsp;', 'Follow Up to Stand Out', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'follow-up-to-stand-out', '', '', '2012-11-12 12:05:27', '2012-11-12 19:05:27', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=309', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(323, 2, '2012-11-20 10:16:25', '2012-11-20 17:16:25', '&nbsp;\n\nLowe''s, Sitel are now adding hundreds of jobs in Albuquerque for their newcustomer service center.  Check out this link for more information on customer service, sales and management jobs.\n<pre>&lt;<a href="http://www.kob.com/article/stories/S2833539.shtml" target="_blank">http://www.kob.com/article/stories/S2833539.shtml</a>&gt;</pre>', 'Lowe''s, Sitel adding Jobs in Albuquerque Now', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'lowes-sitel-adding-jobs-in-albuquerque-now', '', '', '2012-11-20 10:16:25', '2012-11-20 17:16:25', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=323', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(328, 2, '2012-12-01 16:06:09', '2012-12-01 23:06:09', 'Here are some of the job sites you might find useful if you''re looking for a new job in Albuquerque and/or New Mexico.\n\n<strong>Nonprofit agencies</strong> often list their openings at <a href="http://www.centerfornonprofitexcellence.org/jobs">centerfornonprofitexcellence.org/jobs</a>   All levels.\n\n<strong>Medical Jobs</strong>:\n\nUNM Hospitals:<a href="http://hospitals.unm.edu/jobs/"> hospitals.unm.edu</a>\n\nPresbyterian Hospital and clinics:<a href="http://www.phs.org/PHS/careers/"> http://www.phs.org/PHS/careers/</a>\n\nLovelace Hospital: <a href="http://lovelacehealthplan.com/">http://lovelacehealthplan.com/</a>\n\n<strong>Department of Workforce Solutions</strong> has a comprehensive listing of jobs in all industries.  Free and easy to use. <a href="http://www.dws.state.nm.us/"> Jobs in New Mexico</a>\n\n<strong>Albuquerque Journal</strong>:  lots of listings every Sunday.  Good for education, clerical and professional jobs. <a href="http://www.abqjournal.com/jobs/index.html"> Albuquerque Jobs</a>', 'Resources for Jobs in New Mexico', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'resources-for-jobs-in-new-mexico', '', '', '2012-12-01 16:06:09', '2012-12-01 23:06:09', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=328', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(335, 2, '2012-12-02 10:26:34', '2012-12-02 17:26:34', 'Here are some online job boards that my clients have found helpful.  Most will push job openings to your inbox in the fields that you designate.  Registration is usually fast and easy.  And you can also post your resume. If you prefer to browse, just look at the openings without posting. Most can be personalized by location, industry and job title.\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><a href="http://www.careeralerter.com">Career Alerter          </a><a href="http://www.jobing.com/">Jobing.com</a><a href="http://www.simplyhired.com/">         Simply Hired</a></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><a href="http://www.careerbuilder.com/">Career Builder         </a><a href="http://www.indeed.com/">Indeed</a>                <a href="http://www.snagajob.com/">Snag a Job</a></p>\n<p style="padding-left: 30px;"><a href="http://www.monster.com/">Monster</a> <a href="http://www.jobs-to-careers.com">               </a><a href="http://jobs-to-careers.com">  Jobs to Careers</a></p>', 'Online Resources for the Job Search', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'online-resources-for-the-job-search', '', '', '2012-12-02 10:26:34', '2012-12-02 17:26:34', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=335', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(345, 2, '2012-12-03 22:19:28', '2012-12-04 05:19:28', '<pre>This New Mexico fact sheet summarizes the state''s recent \neconomic growthand the role protected public lands play \nin supporting faster job creation. This article includes \ndata on the fastest-growing New Mexico industries. \n\n<a href="http://headwaterseconomics.org/land/west-is-best-value-of-public-lands-nm/" target="_blank">http://headwaterseconomics.org/land/west-is-best-value-of-public-lands-nm/</a></pre>', 'West Is Best: Protected Lands Promote New Mexico Jobs', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'west-is-best-protected-lands-promote-new-mexico-jobs', '', '', '2012-12-03 22:19:28', '2012-12-04 05:19:28', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=345', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(353, 2, '2013-01-07 16:12:13', '2013-01-07 23:12:13', 'The holidays are over. It''s time to get serious about finding that new job. So what''s the first step?\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Setting a goal</strong> is a good place to start.  What are you looking for?  What skills do you want to use in your next job?  What kind of environment would you prefer? Write down all the aspects of work that you want in your next position.</li>\n	<li><strong>Making a plan</strong> is the next step. Use a computer, a calendar, or a notebook.  Write down your goals, your ideas on how to proceed, companies your interested in, people you can contact.</li>\n	<li><strong>Add dates to your plan</strong>. A goal without a date attached is a wish.  Get serious with yourself about how much time you have to devote to your job search.  Make your goals realistic. Don''t forget to include research time. Job seekers who take the time to prepare are more successful than those who "wing" it.</li>\n	<li><strong>Ask for help.</strong> Looking for a job is lonely.  Find a buddy, a support group,or a professional consultant to help you stay on track.</li>\n	<li><strong>Stay positive</strong>. Employers prefer applicants who are upbeat, confident and enthusiastic.</li>\n</ul>', 'Get a Better Job in 2013', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'get-a-better-job-in-2013', '', '', '2013-01-07 16:12:13', '2013-01-07 23:12:13', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=353', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(360, 2, '2013-01-09 17:03:02', '2013-01-10 00:03:02', 'From the Portales News Tribune:\n\nHealth care is currently eastern New Mexico’s hottest industry for training and jobs, according to John Hemphill, manager or Workforce Connection facilities in eastern New Mexico. Renewable energy, wind and solar, is another thriving area for training and jobs\n\nFive of DWS’s top 10 positions in terms of job openings are in health care and related areas, including registered nurses, occupational therapists, physical therapists, speech-language pathologists, and medical scientists. Completing the top 10 list are retail sales persons, food preparation and service, first-line supervisors in retail, customer service representatives, and first-line supervisors in food preparation.\n\nJai Oyler, an agent with Itsquest, a Clovis employment services agency, said there are gaps in many skilled labor areas. Young welders, for instance, are not coming along fast enough to replace those who are retiring, she said. Electric utilities, she said, are facing skilled worker shortages in many key areas.\n\n“They’re seeing shortages of hundreds of thousands of workers nationally over the next 10 years,” she said. She also said Itsquest has been getting requests for construction workers at Cannon Air Force Base and for a variety of positions at Sunland, the Portales-based processor of peanut products, as it readies to reopen after being shut down by the U.S. Food and Drug Administration due to salmonella contamination.\n\nIn addition, she said, the Tres Amigas project near Clovis will need many construction workers when work begins this year.\n\nDWS also publishes a list of “careers in demand.” These are occupations that are expected to see the greatest number of new positions from 2010 to 2020, as a percentage of jobs in place in 2010.\n\n<strong>The top 10 on this list include: </strong>\n<ul>\n	<li>Computer software engineers.</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Personal and home care aides</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Network systems and data communications analysts</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Home health aides</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Industrial engineers</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Computer software engineers, systems software</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Network and computer systems administrators</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Computer security specialists</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Computer systems analysts</li>\n</ul>\n<ul>\n	<li>Pharmacy Technicians</li>\n</ul>', 'Careers in Demand in Eastern New Mexico', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'careers-in-demand-in-eastern-new-mexico', '', '', '2013-01-09 17:03:02', '2013-01-10 00:03:02', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=360', 0, 'post', '', 1),
(376, 2, '2013-02-11 15:47:42', '2013-02-11 22:47:42', 'If you think your resume might need an update or re-write, and you''d like an opinion on how to make it better, send your current document to me as an email attachment (.doc or docx).  You can also send your cover letter if you have one.\n\nI will review your documents and email you back my suggestions on how to improve them, based on your current job goal.  There is no charge for this service.  If you want me to revise your documents, we will discuss that separately.\n\nYou can reach me at 505-235-9753\n\nor<a href="mailto:info@compassrosecareers.com"> info@compassrosecareers.com</a>\n\n&nbsp;', 'Free Critique of Your Current Resume', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'free-critique-of-your-current-resume-2', '', '', '2013-02-11 15:47:42', '2013-02-11 22:47:42', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=376', 0, 'post', '', 0),
(412, 2, '2013-02-12 10:19:25', '2013-02-12 17:19:25', 'New Mexico, not <a title="Get Quote" href="http://www.bloomberg.com/quote/STOCA1:US">California</a> or <a title="Get Quote" href="http://www.bloomberg.com/quote/STONY1:US">New York</a>, is the largest employer of actors as a share of total employment, with more than 15 per 10,000 workers, according to U.S. <a title="Open Web Site" href="http://www.bls.gov/" rel="external">Bureau of Labor Statistics</a> data compiled by Bloomberg.\n<pre>&lt;<a href="http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-02-12/iron-man-s-penthouse-subsidy-brings-acting-jobs-to-new-mexico.html" target="_blank">http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-02-12/iron-man-s-penthouse-subsidy-brings-acting-jobs-to-new-mexico.html</a>&gt;</pre>', 'Acting Jobs In New Mexico', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'acting-jobs-in-new-mexico', '', '', '2013-02-12 10:19:25', '2013-02-12 17:19:25', '', 0, 'http://compassrosecareers.com/?p=412', 0, 'post', '', 0);
